      <h1>Introduction to Lego</h1>
      <section class="intro">
        <h2>What is Lego?</h2>
        <div class="intro-content">
          <img
            src="https://cdn.glitch.global/177012a8-02b8-4480-b72f-8c64793ab958/Lego_Color_Bricks.jpg?v=1734802327147"
            alt="Lego Bricks"
          />
          <p class="general">
            Lego is a versatile and creativity-inducing building toy made up of interlocking plastic bricks. These can be used to create an infinite variety of structures and designs. Lego is known throughout the world for promoting creativity and problem-solving. Lego allows builders to construct anything from simple shapes to complex, detailed creations. With themed sets and customizable pieces, LEGO appeals to people of all ages.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="intro-content">
          <span class="caption">Figure 1. Image of Lego Bricks</span>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section class="history-funfacts">
        <section class="history">
          <h2>Brief History</h2>
          <p>
            Lego, which is a plastic brick-building toy, was created by Ole Kirk
            Christiansen in his hometown Billund, Denmark. He initially created
            wooden toys back in 1932 and named his company LEGO, from the Danish
            phrase Leg godt which meant "play well". In 1949, Lego introduced
            its first plastic brick, which was later patented in 1958 by his
            son. This interlocking brick design quickly gained popularity
            throughout Europe, leading to the opening of the first LegoLand park
            in 1968. Over the years, Lego released lines like DUPLO,
            Minifigures, and the MINDSTORMS robotics kit in 1998.
          </p>
